  "prompt": "What are some animals native to New Zealand?",
  "response": "New Zealand boasts a rich diversity of native wildlife, many of which are unique to the region due to its long geographic isolation. Here are some notable native animals:\n\n### **Birds**\n1. **Kiwi**\n   - **Description**: The kiwi is an iconic, flightless bird and a national symbol of New Zealand. It has a long beak with nostrils at the tip, which it uses to forage for insects and worms.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Nocturnal and elusive, kiwis are known for their distinctive calls and strong sense of smell.\n\n2. **Kea**\n   - **Description**: A large, intelligent alpine parrot with olive-green plumage and a playful nature.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Keas are known for their curiosity and problem-solving abilities, often interacting with humans and their environment in playful ways.\n\n3. **Kakapo**\n   - **Description**: Also known as the owl parrot, the kakapo is a large, flightless bird with distinctive facial discs.\n   - **Unique Traits**: It is critically endangered and notable for being one of the few nocturnal parrots in the world.\n\n4. **T\u016b\u012b**\n   - **Description**: A medium-sized passerine bird with iridescent plumage and a distinctive white tuft under its beak.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Known for its vibrant songs and ability to mimic sounds, the t\u016b\u012b plays a crucial role in pollinating native plants.\n\n5. **Fantail (Piwakawaka)**\n   - **Description**: A small, agile bird with a fanned tail and white spots on its wings.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Highly active and protective, fantails are often seen flitting through forests catching insects.\n\n### **Reptiles**\n1. **Tuatara**\n   - **Description**: A unique reptile often referred to as a \"living fossil,\" representing an ancient lineage that dates back to the age of dinosaurs.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Tuataras have a distinctive third \"parietal\" eye on top of their heads and can live for over a century.\n\n### **Marine Life**\n1. **Hector's Dolphin**\n   - **Description**: One of the smallest and rarest dolphin species in the world, found only in the coastal waters of New Zealand.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Recognizable by their distinctive rounded dorsal fins and playful behavior.\n\n2. **New Zealand Sea Lion**\n   - **Description**: One of the rarest sea lion species, primarily found along the southern coasts of New Zealand.\n   - **Unique Traits**: They have a robust build and are known for their strong swimming abilities.\n\n### **Invertebrates**\n1. **Glowworm (Arachnocampa luminosa)**\n   - **Description**: A species of fungus gnat whose larvae produce bioluminescent light.\n   - **Unique Traits**: Glowworms create mesmerizing light displays in caves and forests, attracting prey with their luminescence.\n\n2. **Giant Weta**\n   - **Description**: Large, flightless insects that resemble oversized crickets.\n   - **Unique Traits**: They are among the heaviest insects in the world and play essential roles in their ecosystems.\n\n### **Mammals**\nNew Zealand is unique in that it has no native land mammals apart from bats. The **Long-tailed Bat** is the only native terrestrial mammal:\n- **Long-tailed Bat**\n  - **Description**: A small, nocturnal bat found throughout New Zealand.\n  - **Unique Traits**: They have long tails and are agile fliers, feeding on insects.\n\n### **Unique Ecosystems and Conservation**\nNew Zealand's isolation has led to the evolution of many endemic species. However, this uniqueness also makes them vulnerable to threats such as habitat loss, introduced predators, and climate change. Conservation efforts are ongoing to protect and preserve these remarkable native animals.\n\nIf you\u2019re interested in learning more or visiting some of these unique species, consider exploring New Zealand\u2019s national parks and wildlife reserves, where many of these animals can be seen in their natural habitats.",
